  "prompt": "What will happen to the border between Northern Ireland and Ireland following the Brexit vote?",
  "response": "Following the Brexit vote, the border between Northern Ireland (which is part of the United Kingdom) and Ireland (an EU member state) became a significant point of concern due to the potential reintroduction of a \"hard border\" with customs checks and physical infrastructure. This issue was sensitive due to the Good Friday Agreement of 1998, which helped to bring peace to Northern Ireland by eliminating the hard border.\n\nTo address this, the UK and EU negotiated the Northern Ireland Protocol, part of the Brexit Withdrawal Agreement. Under this protocol, Northern Ireland remains aligned with certain EU regulations to allow goods to flow freely between Ireland and Northern Ireland without customs checks. Instead, checks are required on goods entering Northern Ireland from the rest of the UK, effectively creating a de facto border in the Irish Sea.\n\nThis arrangement has been controversial and subject to ongoing negotiations to ensure it operates smoothly. The key aim is to prevent a hard border on the island of Ireland, maintaining peace and economic stability, while addressing concerns about trade and regulatory differences arising from Brexit. These matters are subject to ongoing political negotiation and dialogue between the UK, the EU, and local stakeholders.",
